  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here is an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different jurisdictions:\n\n1. United States Approach\n- Bank Secrecy Act and Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations\n- Comprehensive reporting requirements\n- Criminal and civil penalties\n- Strong emphasis on financial institution compliance\n\n2. European Union Approach\n- Unified Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Centralized regulatory framework\n- Emphasis on financial transparency\n- Consistent reporting standards across member states\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Strict Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Sophisticated financial intelligence mechanisms\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Historically more permissive legal framework\n- Strong banking secrecy traditions\n- Gradual implementation of international standards\n- Increasing transparency requirements\n\n5. China\n- Centralized regulatory approach\n- Strict capital controls\n- Growing emphasis on international compliance\n- Criminal penalties for significant violations\n\n6. International Standards\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Global baseline standards for money laundering prevention\n- Mutual evaluation processes\n- Encourages consistent cross-border approaches\n\nThis overview represents a generalized comparative perspective based on established legal frameworks.",
